@{u}Command-Overview@{uu}

  @{b}DOS-COMMANDS@{ub}              @{b}AMIEX-COMMANDS@{ub}         @{b}OTHER COMMANDS@{ub}

   @{"    CD    " LINK CD}               @{"  FLAG/A/F " LINK FLAG}            @{"   CLEAR   " LINK CLEAR}
   @{"   .. /   " LINK PARENT}               @{"   DOWN/D  " LINK DOWN}            @{"   VER/$   " LINK VER}
   @{"   INFO   " LINK INFO}               @{"   VIEW/D  " LINK VIEW}            @{"  HELP/#/? " LINK HELP}
   @{" LIST/DIR " LINK DIR}               @{"   QUIT/G  " LINK QUIT}            @{"   INDEX   " LINK INDEX}
   @{"   TYPE   " LINK VIEW}               @{"  ZIPPY/Z  " LINK ZIPPY}            @{"  CHANGE   " LINK CHANGE}
   @{"  ENDCLI  " LINK QUIT}

@{u}General Usage@{uu}

 @{" LINE-EDITOR " LINK LINE-EDITOR}             @{" DOWNLOADING " LINK DOWNLOADING}          @{"  MARK/FLAG  " LINK MARK&FLAG}
@endnode

@node CD "DOS-COMMAND : CD - CHANGE DIRECTORY"

@{u}CD - Change Directory@{uu}

With this command you could change the current directory, i.e. if you are in
Directory CD0:AMINET/ and you want to go to CD0:AMINET/BIZ/, simply enter
'CD BIZ/' and CD-Server changes the currentdir.

All directories you entered after CD will be searched from the Current dir,
so if CD-Server won't change the directory, this dir doesn't exist or it's
a file, not a dir.

Of course you could change the directory only by entering the Dirname, so CD
is not needed when changing dirs.

@{u}NOTE:@{uu} As special security we have disabled the ':' key to enter it in the
      prompt, if you do it, CD-Server immediatly changes to the Root-Dir
      of the Device, i.e. in dir CD0:AMINET/ pressing ':' results in changing
      the dir to CD0: .

See Chapter @{"Line-Editor" LINK LINE-EDITOR} for more informations about restrictions & special
commands when entering something.
@endnode

@node PARENT "DOS-COMMAND : .. /  - GET PARENT DIR"

@{u}.. / - Change to parent Dir@{uu}

With this commands you could change to parent dir, until you reached the Root
directory (i.e. CD0:) or the Root of the Assign you've entered.

See also Chapter @{"CD - COMMAND" LINK CD}
@endnode

@node INFO "DOS-COMMAND : INFO - GETS INFORMATION ABOUT USED DRIVE"

@{u}INFO - Prints out some informations about used drive@{uu}

This command prints out the same informations you have seen when you started
CD-Server first time. Sample Output looks like :
                                                                     
Device used..: CD0: (AMINET5)                                        
Unit Number..: 0                                                     
Disc Status..: Write protected                                       
R/W Errors...: 0                                                     
File-System..: DOS0 (OFS)                                            
# of Blocks..: 326334                                                
Bytes/Block..: 2048                                                  
Bytes used...: 637 MB                                                
@endnode

@node DIR "DOS-COMMAND : DIR - SHOWS DIRECTORY"

@{u}LIST / DIR - Display Directory-Contents@{uu}

This Command displays the Current directory contents. The output is the same
like in every shell's List - command, so no further informations needed here.

Of course you could always enter an alternate directory to be displayed. If
no path is set, the Current Directory-Contents are displayed.
@endnode

@node VIEW "DOS-COMMAND : VIEW/V/TYPE - DISPLAYS TXT- AND AGUIDE-FILES"

@{u}VIEW/V/TYPE - Displays TXT- & AmigaGuide-Files@{uu}

This Command displays txtfiles or AmigaGuide-Files, which where converted 
first to ANSI, so you could easily read any txtfile found on CD. The usage
is exactly the same like in my mEGA-vIEW , so you should become no problems
when using it :)

To allow CD-Server the converting of Guides, you have to put the program
Guide2DocProf (written by Fox/RMD/ALIENGROUP) to your C: Directory, otherwise
you always see the Guides with all special commands !

@{u}NOTE:@{uu} Please don't view anything else like TXT & Guidefiles, 'coz CD-Server
      is not able to determine which filetype you have selected, and binary
      Files (like *.exe, *.lha) may produce strange results on your screen !
@endnode

@node QUIT "DOS-COMMAND : ENDCLI - QUIT PROGRAM"

@{u}ENDCLI/G/Q/QUIT - Quit Program@{uu}

This Program exists CD-Server, but all flagged files are still in the list!
@endnode

@node FLAG "AMIEX-COMMAND : FLAG - MARK FILES FOR DOWNLOADING"

@{u}FLAG/F/A - Add Files to Download-List@{uu}

This Command is exactly the same like the Amiex-Command (@{"FAME" LINK FAME} has more 
options!), and supports multiargs, too. So you always could enter i.e.
                  
                       A TEST.LHA TH.LHA LABER.LHA

and the files 'TEST.LHA', 'TH.LHA' and 'LABER.LHA' will be flagged from 
current dir.

As special command for flagging this command has a double function:

                                   A C *

It will clear the internal BBS-Flagging List (normal), but under Amiex
also clears ALL pathes known by CD-Server and rejects you to the Root of the 
Device to  avoid problems. So if you use this, there are no more flagged files 
anymore! But under the @{"FAME" LINK FAME} System CD-Server must not keep all pathes in
memory, so this 'A C *' Command under @{"FAME" LINK FAME} only clears the Flaglist and
rejects you to the root.

As special bonus, you could enter a complete pathname to a file not found in
the current directory, i.e. this is a valid call:

                    A README AMINET/BIZ/DBASE/DEMO.LHA

this call produces 1. the flagging of the file 'README' from the current 
directory and 2. splits the filename to 'DEMO.LHA', gives this filename to 
the BBS flag-list,and forces CD-Server to store the path for the downloading 
Procedure (Under Amiex only, @{"FAME" LINK FAME} is able to flag the Path, too!!!). 
This also works with the @{"Download" LINK DOWN}-Command.

@{u}NOTE FOR AMIEX-USERS:@{uu}

You have to live with one restriction when Flagging files...it's not 
allowed to use the '*' as wildcard, coz' Amiex is not able to find those
files in fact of using Multiassign-Lists to store the pathes.

As workaround, instead of using the Wildcard, use the @{"TAB-Key" LINK LINE-EDITOR} for Pathnames-
completition and add only @{b}FULL@{ub} Filenames to the list...I think with the TAB-
key there should be no problems with it!

If AMIEX have trouble anyway to find files, you should @{"register" LINK REGVERSION} yourself
and I'll give you a solution for this Problem, but it's by far not the 
best one....

@{u}NOTE:@{uu} If you have a lost carrier while downloading from CD, and Amiex is
      able to store the flagged list of files, than you have to enter every
      directory and flag the files again, coz CD-Server (btw. Amiex) now
      don't knows anymore the pathes !

@{u}NOTE FOR FAME-USERS:@{uu}

Forgot all the restrictions described below, coz under @{"FAME" LINK FAME} ALL working now,
including the Wildcards, remembering of marked files after a Lost Carrier,
leaving the CD-Server with keeping all tagged files or changing the device
inside CD-Server.

For more detailed informations look in Chapter @{"MARK/FLAG FILES" LINK MARK&FLAG}.
@endnode

@node DOWN "AMIEX-COMMAND : DOWN - DOWNLOAD ALL FLAGGED FILES"

@{u}DOWN/D - Download flagged files from CD@{uu}

Once you have @{"flagged" LINK FLAG} all needed Files, you could download them by using
this command. In fact that this Command is the same like the internal DL, of
course the BBS checks first if you have enough Bytes/Files available for down-
loading. If all fits, CD-Server now begins to download all files. But always
remember, it's the internal Download-Routine, and it's possible that the BBS
breaks the Process while downloading when you have reached you limits !!! So
make sure that you have enough bytes/files free before flagging thousands of
files!

And, as noted in Chapter MARK/FLAG, you could enter filenames after the 'D' -
command, including complete pathes to files found relative to the current dir.

When you see the BBS-Internal Download-Routine asking you to enter another
Filename, you could enter here all files found in the directory, from where
you have started the downloading. Of course it's not allowed to enter here
pathes, as the BBS says then: You don't have to include any special symbols !
@endnode

@node ZIPPY "AMIEX-COMMAND : ZIPPY - SEARCH FILES ON DEVICE OR IN TEXTFILES"

@{u}ZIPPY/Z - Searches files on any device or textfile.@{uu} (Reg. Version only!)

This allows you to perform a Filesearch or a Textsearch. When using the
filesearch, it may take some minutes before CD-Server could find something,
so PLEASE use this only if the selected Device has no Index-Textfile or some-
thing similiar to search for.

When using Text-Search, you were asked for the Filename of the Textfile to
scan for, you could enter here a relative path to the current dir of course.
If the file exists, you were asked for the Searchstring...enter here the
string WITHOUT Patterns, as this is not needed here. If a matching could be
found, CD-Server displays the Text-File from this point on, the found string
will be highlited in green. 

It's recommended to use first the Text-Search before using the File-Search,
as seeking on devices is by far not the best for any device, coz the device
has to jump many times...but if you MUST use it anyway, you were first asked
for the filename to search. Now you were asked if CD-Server should scan all
Subdirs recursivly or only scan current dir. Now if CD-Server found this
entry, you were asked if you want to change to this dir or only display the
found entry.

              @{APEN 2}THIS COMMAND WORKS ONLY IN THE REGISTERED VERSION ! @{APEN 1}
@endnode

@node CLEAR "MISC. COMMAND : CLEAR - CLEARS THE SCREEN"

@{u}CLEAR/CLS - Clears the Screen@{uu}

With this command you could clear the screen...I think nothing more has to be
written for this Command :)
@endnode

@node VER "MISC. COMMAND : VER - SHOWS VERSION-INFORMATIONS"

@{u}VER/$ - Displays Program-Version@{uu}

By entering this command, you get the Program-Version and the Compiling Date
of CD-Server. Of course you could check the Program-Version by using the 
Amiga-Dos Command 'VERSION' to display the Version-Number. Take a look to
your AMIGA-DOS Manual for more informations about this Command.
@endnode

@node HELP "MISC. COMMAND : HELP - SHOWS HELPSCREEN"

@{u}HELP/?/# - Displays the Online-Help@{uu}

If you don't know how a command is written, simply enter HELP and you get
an overview of all CD-Server commands. To allow sysops to built in their
own style, i have made this Online-Help as external File found under the
Path: 'S:CD-SERVER.HLP'. If you don't like the style, simply edit this
file to your own needs.
@endnode

@node INDEX "MISC. COMMAND : INDEX - SEARCH & DISPLAYS THE INDEX-FILE"

@{u}INDEX - Search & Displays the Index-File on Aminet-CD's@{uu}

In fact that I using my CD-Rom mainly for Aminet-CD's, I found out that in
every directory on all Aminet-CD's a file could be found called INDEX. In 
this File all Files from the Current directory are listed with one line of
the .readme Files. So if you want to search for a specific file, simply
enter INDEX and if found, you get the INDEX for the Current Dir.
@endnode

@node CHANGE "MISC. COMMAND : CHANGE - CHANGE CURRENT DEVICE"

@{u}CHANGE - Change current device@{uu} (V1.03)

This command allows you to change the current device and select an other
device or Assign to work on. Under Amiex, all pathes were deleted from
CD-Server's internal List, so if you have flagged files, you should dl
them first befor changing the device!

Under the @{"FAME" LINK FAME}-System, there will be no problems, you could change the
device without loosing all tagged files, flag files from another device,
and then download all tagged files at once.
@endnode

@node LINE-EDITOR "HOW TO WORK EFFICIENT WITH THE LINE-EDITOR"

@{u}Usage of the Line-Editor from CD-Server@{uu}

To give you the maximum comfort on CD, ByteAndi & I have written a very
flexible and comfortable Enter-Routine, allowing you to work in the same
way the wellknown C-Shell works. Here's a list of all special commands:

1) TAB-Key. With this key you are able to complete every filename found. So
   you could enter i.e. 'AMI' and press TAB, CD-Server may now found:
   AMINET/ , AMINET.Z, AMINET etc.. If you only press TAB without entering
   something, the current directory contents will be scanned and the first
   file will be displayed. Another nice function is the shortcut of dirs, 
   meaning if you enter 'CD */*/*/*' and press TAB, you get (on AMINET-CD!)
   maybe the following output (from Rootdir!): 

                        AMINET/BIZ/DBASE/DEMO.LHA

   This works anywhere on the Line, not only on the Beginning, and we think,
   that this Function is the best replacement for the Wildcards...:)
   By the way, if you are with the CRSR near the end of line and press TAB
   to get a filename, it may happen that the filename is too long to fit
   on the rest of the line, in this case CD-Server simply ignores your 
   request!

2) Full Line-Editing. This Feature allowing you to 'walk' through the line
   by using CRSR-Left/right, you could delete some chars inside the line,
   you could insert some chars, delete the whole Line by pressing CTRL-X etc. 
   But always remember, this is a LINE-Edit Routine, meaning that only ONE 
   complete Line is supported, if you reached the end of Line, you have to 
   press Enter and begin a new Line.

3) History-Buffer with Shortcuts. Every Line entered will be stored in an
   internal Buffer, so if you enter many times the same command, simply press
   Cursor-Up/Down, and you get the Last/First line entered. This History-
   buffer allows us to built in another nice feature of C-Shell, meaning the
   Shortcut for commands. Imagine you have entered many times the 'DIR' 
   command, and you get tired of typing evertime the same...so simply enter
   '!D', and CD-Server expands this to 'DIR' ! Other Example: You have 
   entered the Commandline : 'LIST CD0:AMINET/UTIL/' , and you want again
   showing this dir, simply enter '!LI' and CD-Server executes the above
   written command...:)

4) Shortcuts for all commands supported by CD-Server. This allows you to
   use a shortcut for commands, i.e. 'L' for 'LIST', 'C' for 'CLEAR/CLS' etc.

5) Restricted Key ':'. This key has to be disabled for security reasons, by
   pressing it you get immediatly to the Root-directory! So if you want to
   change to Root, enter anywhere this char, and you are in the Root-dir! :)

@{u}NEW IN V1.03@{uu}

6) Pathnames are now cutted if they become longer than 30 Chars. If this
   happen, CD-Server cuts the pathnames in front with three dots (...) to
   indicate that this path is currently not complete visible. This allows 
   the user to enter a minimum of 46 chars, regardeless how long the path-
   name of the current directory is.
@endnode

@node DOWNLOADING "HINTS & TIPS FOR THE DOWNLOADING-PROCEDURE"

@{u}Downloading@{uu}

@{u}NOTES FOR AMIEX-USERS:@{uu}

As we all know, Downloading from Devices, which weren't known by Amiex when
starting it, is not an easy thing. Therefor I have to be tricky when using
this. So it may occure, when two users uses the CD-Server at the same time,
that some files were found twice...this is normal and is no bug, it's one
of the so said 'SIDE-EFFECTS' of this trick :)

Another important thing is the fact, that it's impossible to download a file
with the same filename from two or more different directories! That's because
Amiex searches for the desired Filename only as long as it doesn't find a
match for this Filename. When finding it, Amiex skips to the next filename,
and if this is the Same like the previous name, it says: File is already
selected !
So if you want to download i.e. the file INDEX from CD0:AMINET/ and from
CD0:AMINET/BIZ/, you have to download it first from CD0:AMINET/ by changing
to this directory, then enter 'A C *' (which clears 1. all files in the list 
and 2. the Pathlist), and then entering CD0:AMINET/BIZ/ and download the second 
INDEX file. Sorry for this, but i thought, that the hole comfort of CD-Server 
is a good replacement for those restrictions, eh ? :)

But we make it possible to remove another problem with the downloading, it's
possible to enter i.e.

                      d aminet/biz/dbase/data1.lha 

as argument, this would be converted as 'D DATA1.lha' , and the path you have
entered will be known by CD-Server & the BBS, so you could easily leech this
file without entering the Directory first. This works with the Flagging of
files too!

@{u}NOTES FOR FAME-USERS:@{uu}

Well, what should I say...@{"FAME" LINK FAME} is now able to control the CD-Server without
having this shitty Assign...so all restrictions for Amiex are not valid for
@{"FAME" LINK FAME}-Systems, meaning you could now use the Wildcard, flag many files with
the same filename and the Multinodesupport works now perfect!

So change your BBS-System now, it's worth!
@endnode

@node MARK&FLAG "HINTS & TIPS FOR THE FLAGGING OF FILES"

@{u}Mark/Flag files for downloading@{uu}

@{u}NOTES FOR AMIEX-USERS:@{uu}

As said above, one thing that is not supported is the Flagging of files with
wildcards (*). This will result in not finding the Files, so please @{b}DON'T USE
THIS@{ub}, instead use the TAB-Key (see Chapter @{"LINE-EDITOR" LINK LINE-EDITOR} for more informations)
for Pathname-Completition. This problem is not fixable for amiex as long as 
ByteMaster won't change his Icon-Routines, because he reads the Icon only one
time when starting the Amiex, and gets then all values from Memory. So Amiex
isn't able to recognize new ToolTypes added to the Conference-Icon when 
running Amiex (How about a new command, which forces Amiex to re-load in the
current Conference-Icon, ByteMaster ?) !!!

Amiex has another disadvantage when marking files...the list of flagged files
is not unlimited, it has a limit of 2048 Bytes (or more, don't know exactly)
for the Filenames, so if Amiex breaks the flagging, you have to download first
some files or delete some names from the list. If you are running @{"FAME" LINK FAME}, this 
Problem won't occure, as @{"FAME" LINK FAME} uses REAL DYNAMIC LISTS to store filenames, and 
therefor the list is only limited by your Computer's Memorysize !

As shown in the Chapter @{"DOWNLOADING" LINK DOWNLOADING}, you could of course enter i.e.

                     A aminet/biz/patch/suxx.lha

and CD-Server flaggs only 'suxx.lha' , but remembers the Path, so you could
download this file without entering the path first.

@{u}NOTES FOR FAME-USERS:@{uu}

No restrictions are needed, under @{"FAME" LINK FAME} anything works like the normal flag/dl
routines, but Filenames including Pathes could also flagged..:)
@endnode

